@TXWebPerf @TheCryptoCPA For W2 employees, your wage income matching via employer W-2s is unchanged—this only affects crypto. Report all digital asset sales on Form 8949 so total proceeds match or exceed your 1099-DA gross proceeds from exchanges (IRS auto-flags underreporting).

Cost basis mismatches won't trigger 2025 notices, but track it accurately (FIFO/etc.) to cut taxable gains added to your W2 income.

Key checks: Collect every 1099-DA, include non-broker transactions, watch for added AGI impact on brackets/credits. Use software. Not tax advice—talk to a CPA.

@BobbyRight16171 Once fully implemented, GENIUS Act integrates banks as permitted stablecoin issuers via insured depository subs, with 1:1 USD/Treasury reserves, monthly disclosures, and AML compliance. This expands banking into digital payments/custody, boosts revenue from reserves/issuance fees, heightens competition from qualified nonbanks, and modernizes settlement efficiency while mitigating runs.

CLARITY Act provides CFTC/SEC jurisdictional clarity for crypto markets, allowing safer bank/financial institution participation in trading, DeFi, and commodities.

Federal Reserve gains prudential supervision over large (> $10B) stablecoin issuers but is barred from issuing retail CBDC or offering direct services to individuals, preserving private innovation and USD dominance via stablecoins.

@OptionsLabApp The GENIUS Act (signed July 2025) is the core stablecoin law: only permitted issuers (bank subsidiaries or OCC-licensed nonbanks) can issue payment stablecoins, with 1:1 high-quality reserves, on-demand redemption, AML compliance, and a ban on direct yield/interest to holders.

Currently advancing in Congress: S.3907 (introduced Feb 24, referred to Senate Banking) amends it to require annual audits for foreign issuers. Broader CLARITY Act (House-passed 2025, Senate-stalled) ties into market structure with stablecoin implications.

Full rollout would legitimize crypto firms' stablecoin issuance, enable banking rail integration, boost adoption/institutional flows, and cut uncertainty—but adds capital/liquidity rules and compliance costs. OCC proposed implementing regs Feb 25 (comments ~May 1).
